Clumpy-sphere examples for LaRT_v2.00
======================================

Physical setup
--------------
A point source at the centre of a sphere of radius rmax emits Lyman-alpha
photons (or another resonance line) at line centre.  The sphere contains N
non-overlapping spherical clumps of radius clump_radius, placed by
Random Sequential Adsorption (RSA).  Each clump has uniform opacity
clump_tau0 (line-centre tau from centre to surface), temperature
par%temperature, and optionally a bulk velocity set by clump_sigma_v or
velocity_type.  Outside the clumps the medium is vacuum.

The key dimensionless parameters are:
  N_cov  = (3/4) * N_clumps * (clump_radius / rmax)^2  -- line-of-sight
                                                            covering factor
  tau0   = clump_tau0                                   -- per-clump opacity
  sigma_v                                               -- clump velocity dispersion

Activate with par%use_clump_medium = .true.  (LaRT_v2.00 procedure-pointer interface).
The OOP interface par%grid_type = 'clump' is available in LaRT_v2.10 and later.

Input files
-----------
  clump_tau3_fcov5.in         tau0=1e3, N_cov=5,  static (reference run)
  clump_tau4_fcov5.in         tau0=1e4, N_cov=5,  static (high optical depth)
  clump_tau3_fcov20.in        tau0=1e3, N_cov=20, static (dense covering)
  clump_tau3_fcov5_hubble.in  tau0=1e3, N_cov=5,  Hubble expansion Vexp=200 km/s
  clump_tau3_fcov5_sigv.in    tau0=1e3, N_cov=5,  clump sigma_v=50 km/s
  clump_tau3_fcov5_peel.in    tau0=1e3, N_cov=5,  peel-off observer (129x129 image)

  clump_test.in               legacy single-test case (1e5 photons, same as
                              clump_tau3_fcov5 but with peel-off enabled)

How to run
----------
  cd LaRT_v2.00/examples/clump_sphere
  bash run.sh                            # runs all cases with NP=4
  # or individually:
  mpirun -np 4 ../../LaRT.x clump_tau3_fcov5.in

Output files
------------
  <base>.fits.gz            FITS spectrum: extensions [1] velocity, Jout, Jin
  <base>_obs.fits.gz        peel-off image cube (if save_peeloff = .true.)
  <base>_clumps.fits.gz     clump positions/velocities (if save_clump_info = .true.)

  _clumps.fits.gz BinTable columns: X, Y, Z [code units], VX, VY, VZ [km/s]
  Header keywords: N_CLUMPS, SPHERE_R, CL_RAD, F_VOL, N_COV, TAU0,
                   SIGMA_V, TEMP_CL, RHOKAP, CL_DFREQ, VTHERM, VOIGT_A

Analysis
--------
  python plot_clump.py                   # all runs
  python plot_clump.py clump_tau3_fcov5  # single run

  Produces per-run PDF with spectrum, peel-off image, and clump position
  scatter plot (z-slice), plus a multi-run comparison spectrum PDF.

Key parameters (namelist)
--------------------------
  par%use_clump_medium = .true.   ! selects clump-medium mode (v2.00)
  par%rmax             = 1.0      ! outer sphere radius [code units]
  par%clump_radius     = 0.01     ! individual clump radius [code units]
  par%clump_N_cov      = 5.0      ! line-of-sight covering factor  \
  par%clump_f_vol      = ...      !  or volume filling factor        >  specify one
  par%clump_N_clumps   = ...      !  or number of clumps            /
  par%clump_tau0       = 1.0e3    ! line-centre tau (clump centre -> surface)
  par%clump_nH         = ...      !  or HI density [cm^-3] (needs distance_unit)
  par%clump_temperature = -1.0    ! clump T [K]; -1 uses par%temperature
  par%clump_sigma_v    = 0.0      ! Gaussian sigma of clump bulk velocity [km/s]
  par%velocity_type    = ''       ! 'hubble', 'constant_radial', 'ssh', etc.
  par%save_clump_info  = .true.   ! write *_clumps.fits.gz

Notes
-----
* RSA placement may be slow for f_vol > ~30%.  Use clump_N_clumps instead of
  clump_f_vol in that regime.
* N_cov = (3/4) * N_clumps * (clump_radius/rmax)^2; the effective optical
  depth through the sphere is approximately N_cov * tau0.
* The sightline-tau feature (par%save_sightline_tau) is not supported in clump
  mode (gives tau=0 everywhere because the Cartesian grid has rhokap=0).
* Multi-node runs: clump positions are generated by global rank 0 and broadcast
  so every node uses an identical layout.
